        </section>

        <section id="formulas" aria-labelledby="formulas-heading">
          <h2 id="formulas-heading">The formulas</h2>
          <p>
            Since June 9, 2023 the Army has used a one-site tape method: body weight and abdominal circumference at the navel. Army Directive 2023-11 introduced it. After a one-year transition it became the only authorized tape method on June 8, 2024. The older method used height, neck and other circumference measurements.
          </p>
          <div class="formula-cards">
            <div class="formula-card">
              <h3>Current men</h3>
              <p class="formula">% body fat = &minus;26.97 &minus; (0.12 &times; weight in lb) + (1.99 &times; abdomen in inches)</p>
            </div>
            <div class="formula-card">
              <h3>Current women</h3>
              <p class="formula">% body fat = &minus;9.15 &minus; (0.015 &times; weight in lb) + (1.27 &times; abdomen in inches)</p>
            </div>
            <div class="formula-card">
              <h3>Old men</h3>
              <p class="formula">% body fat = 86.010 &times; log10(abdomen &minus; neck) &minus; 70.041 &times; log10(height) + 36.76</p>
            </div>
            <div class="formula-card">
              <h3>Old women</h3>
              <p class="formula">% body fat = 163.205 &times; log10(waist + hip &minus; neck) &minus; 97.684 &times; log10(height) &minus; 78.387</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p>
            The result is rounded to the nearest whole percent. In the Army's current worked example, a 210&nbsp;lb man with a 35-inch abdomen computes to 17.48%, recorded as 17%. The U.S. Army Research Institute of Environmental Medicine validated the newer equations against dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry (DXA). The study reported an average underestimate of about 1.4% for men and 0.4% for women, so treat the output as an estimate, not a clinical measurement.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="standards" aria-labelledby="standards-heading">
          <h2 id="standards-heading">The standards</h2>
          <p>
            Maximum allowable body fat depends on age and sex (AR&nbsp;600-9, Table B-2). These thresholds have been stable across the 2013, 2019 and 2023-updated versions of the program:
          </p>
          <div class="table-wrap">
            <table>
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th scope="col">Age group</th>
                  <th scope="col">Male</th>
                  <th scope="col">Female</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                {bodyFatStandards.map((row) => (
                  <tr>
                    <th scope="row">{row.group}</th>
                    <td>{row.male}%</td>
                    <td>{row.female}%</td>
                  </tr>
                ))}
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>
          <p>
            Before anyone gets taped, soldiers are screened against the weight-for-height table below (AR&nbsp;600-9, Table B-1). If you are at or under the screening weight for your height and age, you pass the screening outright and no tape test is required. Height is rounded to the nearest whole inch for this table. Half an inch or more rounds up.
          </p>
          <details class="screening-details">
            <summary>Weight-for-height screening table (Table B-1)</summary>
            <div class="screening-table-group" aria-label="Male and female weight-for-height screening tables">
              <div>
                <h3>Male screening weights</h3>
                <div class="table-wrap">
                  <table class="screening-table">
                    <thead>
                      <tr>
                        <th scope="col">Height</th>
                        <th scope="col">Min</th>
                        <th scope="col">17&ndash;20</th>
                        <th scope="col">21&ndash;27</th>
                        <th scope="col">28&ndash;39</th>
                        <th scope="col">40+</th>
                      </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                      {screeningTable.map((row) => (
                        <tr>
                          <th scope="row">{row[0]}</th>
                          <td>{row[1]}</td>
                          {row.slice(2, 6).map((cell) => (
                            <td>{cell ?? "\u2014"}</td>
                          ))}
                        </tr>
                      ))}
                    </tbody>
                  </table>
                </div>
              </div>
              <div>
                <h3>Female screening weights</h3>
                <div class="table-wrap">
                  <table class="screening-table">
                    <thead>
                      <tr>
                        <th scope="col">Height</th>
                        <th scope="col">Min</th>
                        <th scope="col">17&ndash;20</th>
                        <th scope="col">21&ndash;27</th>
                        <th scope="col">28&ndash;39</th>
                        <th scope="col">40+</th>
                      </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                      {screeningTable.map((row) => (
                        <tr>
                          <th scope="row">{row[0]}</th>
                          <td>{row[1]}</td>
                          {row.slice(6).map((cell) => (
                            <td>{cell ?? "\u2014"}</td>
                          ))}
                        </tr>
                      ))}
                    </tbody>
                  </table>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
            <p class="table-footnote">
              Weights in pounds. Soldiers below the minimum weight are referred for medical evaluation. Above 80 inches, add 6&nbsp;lb per inch for males and 5&nbsp;lb per inch for females.
            </p>
          </details>
        </section>

        <section id="process" aria-labelledby="process-heading">
          <h2 id="process-heading">How the assessment actually works</h2>
          <h3>Screening</h3>
          <p>
            The recorder checks height against Table B-1 after rounding it to the nearest inch. Weight is rounded to the nearest pound. The weigh-in is done in PT uniform without shoes. At or under the screening weight: done. No tape test.
          </p>
          <h3>AFT exemption</h3>
          <p>
            Soldiers who scored 465+ on the record Army Fitness Test with at least 80 points in every event are treated as compliant with the body fat standard and are not taped, even if they are over the screening weight (Army Directive 2025-17, September 2025). The exemption lasts until the next record test, at most 8 months for the Regular Army and 12 for Guard and Reserve. It replaced the earlier ACFT 540-point exemption (AD&nbsp;2023-08, rescinded May 31, 2026).
          </p>
          <h3>The tape</h3>
          <p>
            Abdominal circumference is measured at the navel, three times, in the horizontal plane, without compressing soft tissue. The tape must be non-stretch fiberglass. Each reading is rounded down to the nearest half inch. If one reading differs from the other two by more than an inch, a fourth is taken. The average, to the nearest half inch, goes into the equation.
          </p>
          <h3>Failure and appeals</h3>
          <p>
            A failed tape triggers a confirmation tape by a different team. Soldiers who fail both may request a supplemental assessment on DXA, an InBody 770 bioimpedance analyzer or a Bod Pod, if reasonably available. Passing the supplemental test removes the flag. Otherwise the soldier is enrolled in the Army Body Composition Program.
          </p>
          <blockquote>
            <p>
              <em>2026 note:</em> a Department of War memo signed December 18, 2025 (effective January 1, 2026) directs all services to use waist-to-height ratio (WHtR). The upper limit is below 0.55. The memo also stops height-and-weight tables for body composition, sets body fat bands of 18&ndash;26% for men and 26&ndash;36% for women and tightens fitness-test exemptions. As of early 2026 the Army was still writing its policy, so the AR&nbsp;600-9 procedure above remains the published Army standard. The calculator shows WHtR too, because that number is about to matter.
            </p>
          </blockquote>
        </section>

        <section id="sources" aria-labelledby="sources-heading">
          <h2 id="sources-heading">Sources</h2>
          <ol class="sources-list">
            <li>
